    "created_at": "2014-12-10T16:51:05Z",
    "updated_at": "2014-12-10T16:51:05Z",
    "body": "These sections of POSIX are relevant to this issue:\n- http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/utilities/V3_chap02.html#tag_18_09_01 \"2.9.1 Simple Commands\"\n- http://pubs.opengroup.org/onlinepubs/9699919799/utilities/V3_chap02.html#tag_18_06 \"2.6 Word Expansions\"\n\nMy impression is POSIX doesn't require `sh` to perform tilde expansion in command search from `$PATH`.\n\nJust FYI, Dash 0.5.7 doesn't perform tilde expansion for command seach from `$PATH`.\n\n```\n$ PATH='~/gcc47/bin:/usr/bin:/bin'\n$ echo $PATH\n~/gcc47/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n$ export PATH\n$ gcc47 --version\ndash: 8: gcc47: not found\n```\n\n```\n$ PATH=~/gcc47/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n$ echo $PATH\n/home/nodakai/gcc47/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n$ export PATH\n$ gcc47 --version\ngcc47 (GCC) 4.7.4\nCopyright (C) 2012 Free Software Foundation, Inc.\n```\n\nNor does Zsh 5:\n\n```\n$ zsh --version\nzsh 5.0.5 (x86_64-unknown-linux-gnu)\n$ PATH='~/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin'\n$ export PATH\n$ echo $PATH\n~/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n$ which rlwrap\nrlwrap not found\n```\n\n```\n$ PATH=~/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n$ export PATH\n$ echo $PATH\n/home/nodakai/local/bin:/usr/bin:/bin\n$ which rlwrap\n/home/nodakai/local/bin/rlwrap\n```\n",
